Osteomalacia

Clinical aspects

  • Commonest cause is dietary vitamin D deficiency.
  • The prevalence of vitamin D deficiency is particularly high in older adults,
    • Caused by age-associated ⬇ in cutaneous vitamin D production, ⬇ dietary vitamin D intake, and age-dependent intestinal resistance to calcitriol.
  • Symptoms:
    • Bone pain + tenderness, Muscle weakness,
  • Imaging: Reduced bone mineral density. Severe form -> "cod fish" concave vertebrae. Looser zones - insufficiency fractures seen as radiolucent areas in bone seen mostly in femoral neck, femoral shaft and pubic and ischial rami.
  • Labs: ⬇ Ca2+, ⬇ PO43-, ⬇Vitamin D, ⬆ Alkaline phosphatase.
    • Tetracycline stains bands of osteoid. Bands become closer together and wider in osteomalacia.
  • Treatment: 25,000 units once / week for 6 weeks followed by maintenance dose of 600 / week, Calcium supplementation
  • Expected outcome: Dramatic improvement of symptoms within a few weeks.

Basic Sciences

See [[Calcium Metabolism and Disorders.canvas|Calcium Metabolism and Disorders]]
[[Hormone Physiology#Vitamin D]]

Activated vitamin D (1,25 dihydroxyvitamin D) regulates gene transcription by binding to intracellular receptors.
Mechanism: dihydroxycholecalciferol binds to it's receptor and acts as a transcription regulator which increases calbindin D proteins.
Calbindin increases intestinal calcium absorption.
Induction of another protein in the renal tubules increases renal calcium absorption.
Induction of TRVP5 in the proximal convoluted tubules increases renal calcium absorption.

  • High Serum calcium and phosphate concentrations -> Negative feedback by (and vice versa)
  • Fibroblast growth factor 23 ([[#Phosphate physiology|FGF23]]) (FGF23 inhibits renal production of 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D)

[!INFO] FGF23 requires 'Klotho' to function.
Loss of function mutations of Klotho or FGF23 cause similar phenotypes of increased ageing and shorter lifespan, hyperphophatemia, and increased vitamin D3 level

Main action is to 'mobilize calcium from bone' and increase renal phosphate excretion.
In hypoparathyroidism, there is increased bone minieral density. But the bone is not properly formed.
